'''James Bodell''' ({{Circa|1831}} – 23 September 1892) was a New Zealand soldier, businessman, local politician and writer. He was born in [[Arnold, Nottinghamshire|Arnold]], [[Nottinghamshire]], England and was [[Mayor of Tauranga]] between 1888 and 1889.<ref name="DNZB Bodell">{{DNZB|||1b24|Bodell, James|27 May 2016||Keith Sinclair|Keith Sinclair}}</ref>

==Early life==
The son of framework knitter William Bodell and his wife, Maria Margrom, James Bodell was baptized in [[Arnold, Nottinghamshire|Arnold]] – a town in the [[England|English]] [[Ceremonial counties of England|ceremonial county]] of [[Nottinghamshire]] – on 3 July 1831. The family soon relocated to [[Leicester]], a city around {{Convert|30|mile|km}} away, where Bodell attended school for three years.<ref name="DNZB Bodell"/>

;Enlistment
Bodell enlisted in the [[59th (2nd Nottinghamshire) Regiment of Foot]] in 1848, the year of [[Revolutions of 1848|a series of revolutions]] in Western and Central Europe.<ref name="DNZB Bodell"/>

==Later life==
His memoirs, edited by Sir [[Keith Sinclair]], were published in 1982 as ''A Soldier’s View of Empire''.<ref>''A Soldier’s View of Empire: The Reminiscences of James Bodell 1831-92'' edited by [[Keith Sinclair]].  London, The Bodley Head.</ref>

